{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01C1b21cBaCg4CguX54mPoKq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_019wcedWayQ9dtZQYn3ewFME","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The primary translator produces a grammatically coherent translation that preserves meaning, not word-for-word substitution","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This tests the actual neural model's output quality. A mock API returning a hardcoded response will never catch when the real API produces a bad translation—we'd only discover this failure in production. To catch it, you must call the actual neural translation service. Once you have real output, you can verify coherence through spot-checking against expected translations or using heuristics (sentence structure, word count, presence of key terms). This is a System-level dependency (external API call), not lower, because any mock completely hides the failure mode. If you wanted automated quality evaluation across all inputs, that would require an Agentic evaluation service, but spot-checking with real API output at System level is the production-realistic minimum.","test_description":"Call the real neural translation API with a diverse set of test inputs (e.g., technical text, conversational text, idiomatic phrases in source language). For each output, verify it preserves the semantic meaning (spot-check that key terms are translated correctly, sentence structure is grammatical, and the output is not a word-by-word literal substitution). Log failures for manual review.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test description requires the real external API (System level), not a mock. Spot-checking manual verification or heuristics work at System; a true automated quality oracle would raise to Agentic.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.6,"Agentic":0.3,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":2,"d